Project proposal 
Voice-to-Text Medical Record Generator for Doctors 
1. Introduction 
Medical documentation is an essential part of healthcare, but it is also time-consuming and 
often burdensome for doctors. They must record patient symptoms, diagnosis, prescriptions, 
and follow-up instructions after every consultation. This manual process leads to delays, 
reduced efficiency, and increased chances of human error. 
To address this challenge, the Voice-to-Text Medical Record Generator aims to automate 
the creation of structured medical records from doctors' voice inputs. By leveraging modern 
Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) models such as Whisper and Natural Language 
Processing (NLP) techniques, the system converts audio recordings into organized and 
professional medical documents. This tool improves accuracy, saves time, and promotes the 
digital transformation of healthcare documentation. 
2. Problem Statement 
Doctors frequently speak their observations verbally during patient interactions but must 
later convert these spoken notes into written medical records. This manual transcription 
process can be slow and inefficient, especially during busy clinical hours. 
There is a need for an automated system that can reliably convert a doctor’s voice recording 
into a well-formatted medical report, reducing documentation workload and improving 
consistency. 
3. Objectives 
The primary objectives of this project are: 
1. To convert doctor-recorded audio (WAV/MP3) into accurate text using a speech-to
text model. 
2. To analyze and structure the transcribed text into meaningful medical sections such 
as symptoms, diagnosis, medications, and follow-up instructions. 
3. To develop a user-friendly web interface (Streamlit or Flask) for uploading audio files 
and generating medical reports. 
4. To provide the final output in a structured, readable, and downloadable format 
(TXT/PDF). 
5. (Optional) To evaluate transcription quality using sample datasets and accuracy 
metrics. 
4. Methodology 
4.1 Audio Input and Preprocessing 
The system takes audio recordings from doctors. Public datasets (e.g., Medical Speech 
Transcription Dataset, Mozilla Common Voice) or manually recorded samples are used for 
testing. Basic preprocessing such as noise reduction and normalization may be applied. 
4.2 Speech-to-Text Conversion 
• Whisper/OpenAI ASR model will be used for high-quality transcription. 
• The model handles different accents, medical terms, and background noise 
efficiently. 
• The output is displayed as the raw transcript. 
4.3 NLP-Based Structuring 
A custom NLP module extracts important clinical details using rule-based and keyword
based approaches. Sections include: 
• Patient Information 
• Symptoms 
• Diagnosis 
• Prescribed Medicines 
• Tests & Investigations 
• Follow-up Instructions 
These extracted components are formatted into a clean medical record template. 
4.4 User Interface Development 
A simple web interface will be built with Streamlit or Flask that allows users to: 
• Upload an audio file 
• View the transcription 
• View the structured report 
• Download or copy the final record 
4.5 Tools & Technologies 
• Python 
• Whisper ASR Model (OpenAI) 
• Streamlit/Flask 
• NLTK / spaCy (for NLP) 
• PyTorch 
• NumPy, Pandas 
5. Expected Outcomes 
• A fully working system that converts doctors’ audio notes into structured medical 
records. 
• High transcription accuracy for medical speech. 
• Faster documentation process for healthcare professionals. 
• A simple and effective web-based interface for real-time usage. 
6. Scope and Limitations 
Scope 
• Works for English medical dictation. 
• Supports doctor-recorded audio files. 
• Produces structured text output. 
Limitations 
• ASR accuracy may decrease with heavy noise or unclear speech. 
• Not integrated with hospital EMR systems in the current version. 
• Does not verify or interpret medical correctness of content. 
7. Future Enhancements 
• Multi-language transcription (Telugu, Hindi, etc.). 
• Medical terminology fine-tuning for higher accuracy. 
• Real-time audio streaming from mobile or mic. 
• Integration with electronic medical record systems. 
8. Conclusion 
The Voice-to-Text Medical Record Generator is an innovative solution aimed at reducing the 
documentation burden on doctors. By combining speech recognition and NLP, it automates 
the creation of structured medical records, improving efficiency and accuracy in clinical 
settings. This project has practical real-world value and contributes to the advancement of 
AI-powered healthcare tools.
